{"add":{"doc":{"id":"68b1e3f6b0cb019c0cbf7dadfcd89730d84d8e06faa22e265d7e816bb36626a6","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Huang_Tingjian_Fu_Bo_Shen_Ci.jpg/220px-Huang_Tingjian_Fu_Bo_Shen_Ci.jpg","previous":["Although women were on a lower social tier than men (according to Confucian ethics), they enjoyed many social and legal privileges and wielded considerable power at home and in their own small businesses. As Song society became more and more prosperous and parents on the bride's side of the family provided larger dowries for her marriage, women naturally gained many new legal rights in ownership of property.[54] Under certain circumstances, an unmarried daughter without brothers or a surviving mother without sons could inherit one-half of her father's share of undivided family property.[55][56][57] There were many notable and well-educated women, and it was a common practice for women to educate their sons during their earliest youth.[58][59] The mother of the scientist, general, diplomat, and statesman Shen Kuo taught him essentials of military strategy.[59] There were also exceptional women writers and poets, such as Li Qingzhao (1084–1151), who became famous even in her lifetime.[54]"],"after":["Religion in China during this period had a great effect on people's lives, beliefs, and daily activities, and Chinese literature on spirituality was popular.[60] The major deities of Daoism and Buddhism, ancestral spirits, and the many deities of Chinese folk religion were worshipped with sacrificial offerings. Tansen Sen asserts that more Buddhist monks from India travelled to China during the Song than in the previous Tang dynasty (618–907).[61] With many ethnic foreigners travelling to China to conduct trade or live permanently, there came many foreign religions; religious minorities in China included Middle Eastern Muslims, the Kaifeng Jews, and Persian Manichaeans.[62][63]"]}}}